en.expected_results:
AT-VIRTUAL main results will be: 
- The increased digitalization status of the MSTCs in the Atlantic Area through the adoption of state-of-the-art I4.0 technologies; 
- The increased number of technological solutions validated to resolve MSTCs challenges and problems in the Atlantic Area, ready to be on the market. Baselines for both results will be determined in detail at the beginning of the project through the diagnosis phase.

en.expected_outputs:
- The new solutions piloted and implemented in the MSTCs, contributing to the resolution of the challenges tackled by these centres within the Atlantic Area and resulting in an increased digitalization status;
- The advanced platform created within the project for the speed-up of digitalization processes through open innovation and hybridization, on which its three phases will be carried on (diagnosis of digital status and needs, selection of the most appropriate solutions and prototyping of the solutions);
- A Report and Action Plan on the Digitalization in MSTCs of the Atlantic Area, including their main needs and potentials as well as actions to promote the adoption of I

4.0 solutions.

en.expected_results:
• A joint application to public and/or private call to continue monitoring the artificial reefs after the end of the project and strategic reports and guidance to influence public authorities, environmental bodies and policy makers to adopt 3DPARE technology; 
• Review of the characteristics of natural reefs in the Atlantic Coast in Europe associated with a high biodiversity, as well as an identification of the best practices used so far in the development of the artificial reefs; 
• Sustainable materials for artificial reefs: results will be technical reports of the materials developed, their mechanical properties, their durability to the sea water and their life-cycle assessment study; 
• Pilot artificial reefs: comprising 4 actions whose main result is the selection of the artificial reefs design 3D printable more suitable for the Atlantic Area from a biodiversity, durability and economic point of view.

- Suitable Environmental Quality Standards (EQSs) for metals to allow use of diffusive gradients in thin-films (DGTs) in Water Framework Directive (WFD) compliance monitoring and water chemical status classifications. WFD classifications will feed into assessments of good environmental status at the (sub-) regional scale under Descriptor 8 of the Marine Strategy Framework Directive (MSFD) and consequently application of MSFD may improve with DGT use;
- Framework for further development of EQSs for other priority substances and emerging contaminants that cannot be included within MONITOOL scope;
- Robust comparison of real-world data measured in DGTs and in spot samples from across Atlantic Area with proposed EQSs and existing EQSs to show the approach utility over the whole region. Data from North Sea and Mediterranean Sea will be used to show applicability of approach beyond Atlantic region;
- Improved status assessments for metals that have greater scientific validity and will better withstand public scrutiny in event of failures occurring and expensive measures being required.
